OK HOSTING,2016-04-21T14:53:55.023Z,318,729,"Open source multi-platform UI framework. Create your apps once on PCL and have your UI generated on runtime for ASP.NET, Windows Forms, WPF, Linux (Mono + WinForms), Mac OS (Mono + WinForms and Xamarin.Mac), iOS, Android, Windows Phone (via Xamarin.Forms) and Windows Universal Platform.

column4: * Create your apps in PCL and run them everywhere, truly multi-platform (web included)
* The UI is defined from code (XAML designer on the way)
* 100% native controls are used in all platforms
* You have only the ""common"" UI api surface among all platforms
* Supports click, doble click and, for user input controls, value changed events
* Using OKHOSTING.UI.CSS you can use CSS files to define the styles of your controls on all platforms (thanks to AngleSharp)
* Create forms for user data input/output
* Create form fields for string, int, decimal, date, enum, bool, xml or any custom type you need
* Create forms to execute a method

Please visit: https://github.com/okhosting/OKHOSTING.UI",OKHOSTING.UI,False,2017-06-06T15:21:25.867-07:00,True,False,"Open source multi-platform UI framework. Orthogonal Programming,2016-03-05T22:07:39.35Z,261,776,"The LiteComms library contains two lightweight classes that allows client-server communication, either on the same machine or between different machines on a local area network. The library is intended to be as simple to use as possible and to have a tiny runtime footprint. The client and server classes communicate using a very simple protocol implemented as a single server method that takes a string request and returns a string response. Although this protocol is simple, applications are free to exchange strings between the client and server in any convenient or suitable format they choose. Exchanging strings of XML for example is an easy way to create an extensible general purpose contract between client and server. The LiteComms library is intended for use where network communications between application components must be implemented simply and easily, with no configuration and no complicated dependencies. The library internally uses a TCP/IP Remoting channel for communication.",Orthogonal.LiteComms,False,2017-08-02T13:38:13.473+00:00,True,False,A lightweight communication library that very easily allows client-server style exchange of string messages. Communications is implemented using a TCP/IP Remoting Channel.,orthogonal,1674,False,1.0.2

Greg Keogh,2016-02-17T10:59:18.16Z,621,793,"Author's note: In recent years I was frustrated in attempts to find a public, documented and comprehensible managed library for manipulating ID3 tagged files. As the project Wiki page explains, in 2014 I reluctantly created this library to satisfy the requirement for an easy-to-use lightweight library that can manipulate all of the most commonly encountered features of the ID3 informal standards. Because the ID3 specification is so ridiculously complicated and because only a small subset of its features and versions are in common use, the NTagLite library is deliberately designed to be ""lightweight"" in the sense that it supports only the most common and practically useful subset of ID3 features. This subset is still a significant part of the full specification. The library can parse v2.2, v2.3 and v2.4 tags, but it only supports writing v2.3 tags.",Orthogonal.NTagLite,False,2016-08-07T00:54:50.173-07:00,True,False,A lightweight library for manipulating ID3 tagged files.,,2866,False,2.0.8

Orthogonal Programming,2016-03-05T22:02:21.87Z,30,776,"Author's note: The library was created back in the earliest days of .NET because I needed a place to accumulate bits of reusable utility code and classes. Over a period of several years the library grew quite large and jumbled as a wide variety of code accumulated inside it. Now in recent years the library has shrunk dramatically as newer .NET Frameworks and Nuget packages with expanded functionality have made of lot of the library redundant. The code that remains in the current library is somewhat ""geeky"" and contains some interesting sample functionality related to random numbers, cryptography, checksums, maths and ID3 tagged files. column4: * Create your apps in PCL and run them everywhere, truly multi-platform (web included)
* The UI is defined from code (XAML designer on the way)
* 100% native controls are used in all platforms
* You have only the ""common"" UI api surface among all platforms
* Supports click, doble click and, for user input controls, value changed events
* Using OKHOSTING.UI.CSS you can use CSS files to define the styles of your controls on all platforms (thanks to AngleSharp)
* Create forms for user data input/output
* Create form fields for string, int, decimal, date, enum, bool, xml or any custom type you need
* Create forms to execute a method

column1: Okta,2016-04-21T04:29:07.763Z,359,729,"This package allows you to build on Okta's identity platform using .NET
Supported Platforms:
* .NET Framework 4, 4.5, 4.5.6
* Windows 8, 8.1, 10
* Windows Phone 8.1
* Silverlight 5
* Portable Class Libraries
Update Log
- v0.2.8.0: Bug fix (AuthResponse.FactorResult)
Added support for MFA verification (OTP, Okta Verify and SMS only) at authentication time
Added support for the automation of the creation of WS-Fed application (+AppsClient test class)
Added ability to retrieve a user factor based on its id
Added support for Password Expiration Warning and Multi Optional MFA Enroll
Added ChangePassword and Skip methods in AuthClient (Password Warn flow)
Enhanced Session object (added previously unexposed properties, such as ExpiresAt)
Added GetRefreshUri method on ApiClient
Fixed Extend endpoint for Session objects (SessionsClient)

- v0.2.4.0: Added Advanced Search support",Okta.Core.Client,False,2017-04-26T22:43:22.417+00:00,True,False,Official .NET SDK for Okta,"okta,sdk,api,authentication,identity,management",42941,False,0.2.8
